<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DPRK Developments `Closely' Watched </H4>

<F P=102> OW0206050294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 2 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0206050294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 2 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] As the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
has practically issued an ultimatum on the inspection of nuclear 
fuel rods in relation to the DPRK's (North Korea) suspected 
development of nuclear devices, the government says: "We will 
reach a conclusion in the next few days." 
  According to a top government official Japan is closely 
watching moves by both North Korea and the United States. 
  The government's basic understanding is that the DPRK does 
not recognize IAEA as a viable negotiating partner, and it wants 
to break the deadlock through negotiations with the United 
States. 
  At the House of Representatives Budget Committee on 1 June, 
Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa said: "North Korea wants to give 
priority to talks with the United States. It is not responding 
to Japan's persuasion." 
  He said that although Japan has been talking with the DPRK 
unofficially through its embassy in Beijing and its UN mission, 
such efforts had been unsuccessful. 
  Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata told the committee: "We are 
seriously concerned. We hope to somehow win [the DPRK's] 
understanding through dialogue." 
  He stressed Japan's position of approaching this issue 
through dialogue. 
  Kakizawa also said: "If the nuclear issue is resolved, we 
would like to go into negotiations to normalize diplomatic 
relations." 
  The normalization of ties would include economic assistance 
to the DPRK. 
  Kakizawa also talked about measures relating to possible UN 
sanctions, and indicated that the government was considering 
signing an acquisition and cross-servicing agreement (ACSA) to 
enable offering refuelling and other services to U.S. Forces. 
  Apparently, while the government's basic position is to 
promote dialogue, but it is also dealing with the possibility of 
sanctions, adopting a carrot-and-stick strategy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27421 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas106__a94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-106-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Foreign Ministry `Distressed' </H4>

<F P=102> OW3105060894 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105060894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the DPRK's (North Korea) 
suspected development of nuclear devices, the Japanese 
Government is again distressed by the deadlock in negotiations 
between North Korea and the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) on the replacement of nuclear fuel rods at the Yongbyon 
experimental nuclear reactor, because it has been counting on a 
better atmosphere for dialogue after the third round of 
high-level talks between the United States and North Korea was 
scheduled to be held in June. 
  Under the circumstances, Japan will have to continue to take 
a two-pronged stand for some time by "closely watching future 
developments while studying various necessary measures to 
prepare for a contingency" (according to a top Foreign Ministry 
official). 
  In the past few days, senior Foreign Ministry officials have 
been emphasizing the "dominant trend of dialogue" to leaders of 
the ruling and opposition parties, saying: "Things are moving 
toward a solution right now. There should be no 
misunderstanding concerning this." The ministry is concerned 
that if "frightening discussions" on questions such as sanctions 
or legislation to deal with an emergency come to the fore, this 
may provoke not only the DPRK but also the ROK and the United 
States. 
  The working-level meeting between Japan, the United States, 
and South Korea in New York on 24 May which agreed on continuing 
the policy of dialogue and coordination between the three 
nations if sanctions are imposed on the DPRK was a cooperative 
gesture in line with the U.S. policy of continuing the dialogue. 
  However, after the North Korea-IAEA talks broke down, a 
pessimistic view is again gaining ground inside the government. 
Some say: "We have been betrayed by North Korea so many times. 
This time, although we have not been optimistic, we were hoping 
for at least some progress" (according to a Foreign Ministry 
source). 
  Some government officials now take the view that the 
high-level talks between the United States and North Korea will 
inevitably have to be postponed. Even in the United States, the 
prevailing view is now in favor of sanctions, claiming, "If 
U.S.-North Korean talks are held without verifying the existence 
of nuclear arms in the DPRK, this will just be falling into the 
North Korean trap." 
  If no improvement is seen in this situation, UN economic 
sanctions will inevitably become the focal issue. The Japanese 
Government may also be forced to make a major decision. 
  Even if the third round of high-level U.S.-DPRK talks are 
held as scheduled, it is entirely possible that North Korea will 
continue to play the nuclear card in the future. It is believed 
that "sooner or later, there will have to be a solution to the 
basic issue of whether inspections will be permitted at two 
facilities, which were not opened to IAEA and are highly 
suspected of holding nuclear devices," according to a Foreign 
Ministry source. Days of anxiety are expected to continue for 
the Japanese Government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27422 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas106__a94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-106-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata Stresses Dialogue With DPRK </H4>

<F P=102> OW3105134394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 May 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At a House of Representatives' Budget Committee 
meeting on 30 May, Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata was asked about 
the collapse of talks between the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) and Pyongyang over the inspection of fuel rods 
being removed from a nuclear reactor in the DPRK. Hata said: 
"I have repeatedly asked the United States and South Korea to 
tenaciously talk with Pyongyang. On the other hand, I have 
asked North Korea to consider the anxiety in the international 
community." He then stressed that he intended to work with 
concerned nations to resolve the nuclear issue through talks 
with Pyongyang. 
  Hata also said: "I have told Pyongyang (if the country 
agrees to settle the issue through talks) Japan will help 
improve the DPRK's living standards together with the United 
States, South Korea, and China." In this way, he indicated that 
North Korea would be offered multinational support and 
cooperation if it agreed to resolve the issue through dialogue. 
  Hata was answering questions from Yoshio Hachiro (a member 
of 
the Social Democratic Party of Japan). 
  Concerning the fuel rod removal Pyongyang has arbitrarily 
carried out, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa also said: "If the 
situation remains as it is now, it will become difficult in the 
next few days to confirm the fuel rod exchange," indicating the 
nuclear problem would reach the crucial point in the next few 
days. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

