<H4>    Tokyo on Agreement With U.S. </H4>

<F P=102> OW0206044394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 2 Jun 
94 -- FOR OOFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0206044394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 2 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa said on 1 June that 
when U.S. Forces enforce a sea blockade against the DPRK (North 
Korea) over the issue of its nuclear weapons development: 
"Generally speaking, Japan will offer possible cooperation 
within the constitutional limitation." 
  He was also asked the government's attitude toward the U.S. 
proposal for an "acquisition and cross-servicing agreement 
(ACSA)," an accord aimed at the mutual provision of military 
supplies and services between Japan and the United States. 
  He said the government was studying possibility of enacting 
such an agreement, saying: "To design the framework of the 
concept, the government is studying various aspects, including 
the need for the ACSA." 
  Kakizawa made his remarks in reply to questions by 
Representative Taro Nakayama of the Liberal Democratic Party 
during the 1 June session of the lower house budget committee. 
  Director General Atsushi Kanda of the Defense Agency said 
that as far as North Korea's preparations for the test launching 
of new-type missiles are concerned: "We are watching 
developments with great concern." 

</TEXT>

