<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Tokyo on Possible DPRK Missile Test </H4>

<F P=102> OW0106120694 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 1 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0106120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on North Korea's plans to test-fire a 
missile, a government source said on 31 May that the DPRK will 
test- fire the missile on 7 May at the earliest. The Defense 
Agency [DA], which has placed itself on alert, is trying to 
collect information. 
  The United States has provided the DA with information 
compiled on the basis of photographs taken by U.S. 
reconnaissance satellites. According to that data, trucks loaded 
with fuel and cranes are assembling at a launch site in 
northeastern North Korea, and the missile's test-launching 
process is under way. The DPRK was expected to test-fire the 
missile in early June, but the prevailing view is that North 
Korea will test-fire it on 7 June because of information 
indicating that North Korea needs a few more days to make final 
preparations for the launch. 
  The missile to be test-fired is believed to be the Nodong-1, 
which has a range of 1,000 km and which was test-fired last May. 
  The DA has put Maritime Self-Defense Force P3-C 
antisubmarine 
aircraft on a state of alert to ready them for patrols over the 
Sea of Japan. The Air Defense-Self Force also has placed YS-11E 
electronics reconnaissance aircraft and E2-C airborne warning 
and control aircraft on standby status. In this way, DA is 
making preparations to collect a variety of information on North 
Korea's test-firing of the missile. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

