<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   LDP's Mori on Possible Election Under Multiseat System </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    LDP's Mori on Possible Election Under Multiseat System </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3105133294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 May 
94 Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP], gave a news conference on the morning of 
29 May in Sapporo city, in which he discussed the possibility of 
dissolving the Diet, and calling for general elections 
immediately after the passage of the fiscal 1994 budget. He 
said, "The ruling parties believe that holding elections under 
the multiseat constituencies system means a sabotage of 
political reform. This is aimed at creating confusion inside 
the LDP and the Social Democratic Party of Japan. It is 
possible for all party heads to gather and decide on certain 
necessary measures." This indicated that Mori believes that if 
all parties agree to introduce the "heiritsu" system of 
combining single-seat constituencies and proportional 
representation in the election after the next one, it is also 
possible to hold the next election under the multiseat system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

