<DOCNO> FBIS4-27499 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas106_c_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Issues Statement on UNSC `Allegations' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Issues Statement on UNSC `Allegations' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0206012294 Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2100 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0206012294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang Korean Central Broadcasting Network 
in Korean 2100 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry of the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea [DPRK] issued a statement 
on 1 June refuting the UN Security Council [UNSC] president's 
statement of unreasonable allegations of finding fault with us, 
which was released a few days ago. 
  Press statement of a spokesman of the DPRK Foreign Ministry: 
  The UN Security Council, on May 30, according to a scenario 
which had been worked out in advance by some member states, 
published a statement of its president groundlessly finding 
fault with us and containing the unreasonable claim that the 
fuel rods must be replaced only in compliance with the practical 
demands of the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] and 
that the opportunity for selecting fuel rods for separation and 
preservation might be lost. 
  It is entirely unjust for the UN Security Council to have 
discussed our question without any justifiable reason on the 
basis of the wrong judgment made by the Secretariat of the IAEA. 
It was only a few days ago that negotiations on the replacement 
of fuel rods of the 5 megawatt experimental atomic power station 
were held between us and the agency. 
  The main question discussed at the negotiations was the 
preservation of technical possibilities of future measurement of 
replaced fuel rods and, in particular, there was sufficient 
debate on the reasonableness of the method we are applying at 
present. 
  The agency side, too, said it would seriously study our 
method and the two sides agreed to continue to discuss it in 
future negotiations. 
  And it was confirmed that none of the fuel rods being 
replaced were diverted for other purposes and, practically, that 
the whole course of the current replacement of fuel rods is 
going on in the presence of agency inspectors and under strict 
control of inspection equipment. 
  By the way, what justification on earth does the UN Security 
Council have to put our question on its agenda and discuss it 
now. 
  If things were to take a correct track, the UN Security 
Council should have called, not us, but some quarters of the 
agency secretariat, into question. 
  Before starting to replace fuel rods, on several occasions, 
we requested that the agency take necessary measures such as its 
presence and the removal of the seals. But it did not send a 
team of inspectors to the end, when the replacement of fuel rods 
began, thus openly neglecting its duty as an international 
organization. This was what some quarters of the IAEA 
Secretariat did. 
  Even when we allowed "an additional inspection" which 
alluded 
to "an inspection left incomplete," they shunned it, thus 
intentionally ignoring the statement of the president of the UN 
Security Council dated March 31. 
  It was also the agency's Secretariat that distorted the fact 
by talking as if the negotiations had broken down and hurriedly 
referred our problem to the UN Security Council without a clear 
explanation, categorically denying our method even before the 
negotiating delegation of the agency, which had promised to 
study the method, arrived at the head office in Vienna. 
  In all, such an act by the Secretariat of the IAEA was aimed 
at capping us ultimately with the title of culprit [pigo] by 
justifying their past behavior in concocting, by any means, 
"inconsistency" against us on the basis of fabricated 
information. 
  It is only too natural that our country, which has engaged 
itself only in peaceful nuclear activities as a dignified, 
independent, sovereign state, will not yield to such 
unreasonable act of the agency's Secretariat and allow itself to 
be treated as an offender [choein]. 
  In view of this, the UN Security Council, instead of finding 
fault with us, should have taken issue with some officials of 
the IAEA Secretariat who laid hurdles in the way of our peaceful 
nuclear activities, framed sinister political intrigue to shift 
the blame on to us and referred the problem to the UN. 
  It is also self-contradictory that the presidential 
statement 
of the UN Security Council unreasonably urged us to allow 
selected separation and preservation of fuel rods and 
preservation of the possibility of future measurement. 
  Since we are in a unique status after the temporary 
suspension of the effectuation of our declared withdrawal from 
the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, it is clear that we cannot 
accept such routine and ad hoc inspection as the selected 
preservation of fuel rods. A full understanding of this was 
reached at the recent negotiations with the agency. 
  Although we are replacing the fuel rods in a unique status, 
we are doing the utmost to show the transparency of our nuclear 
activities. 
  The replacement of fuel rods is taking place in such a way 
as 
to fully preserve the technical possibility of measuring the 
fuel rods in the future as requested by the agency when our 
unique status comes to an end. 
  This is the most scientific and realistic method invented by 
our scientists and facility operators with a high sense of 
cooperation, motivated by their consistent position to show the 
uprightness of the nuclear activities. Its feasibility has 
already been proven fully through experiments. 
  If this method of our style is applied, it will be possible 
to reproduce the channel and order of any fuel rods and measure 
them correctly in the future. 
  At the recent negotiations in Pyongyang, we gave the IAEA 
side a full explanation of our-style method concerning the 
replacement of fuel rods and suggested with a good intention 
that negotiations should be held any time if there were any more 
questions to be discussed. 
  There have been attempts these days to create the "urgency" 
of the situation by alleging that the pace of the replacement of 
fuel rods is too fast. Since it is part of the pure peaceful 
nuclear activities and technical possibilities for ensuring the 
continuity of safeguards and measuring fuel rods in the future 
are fully guaranteed, there is no ground for finding fault with 
the speed of replacing fuel rods. 
  It was necessary to test the maximum efficiency of the 
refueling machine that our replacement of fuel rods progressed 
at a rather fast speed some time ago. This was also a normal 
course of the peaceful nuclear activities. So, this is hardly a 
matter for surprise. 
  Such being the case, at a time when everything is 
progressing 
smoothly on a normal track, the UN Security Council discussed 
the biased report submitted by some officials of the Secretariat 
of the agency without any examination and hurriedly adopted a 
presidential statement. It is hardly understandable. 
  This was because they were too dull to sense the reality or 
they were affected by some sinister political background. 
  If the UN Security Council, for this matter, is 
disgracefully 
charged with being manipulated by some specified member nations 
while ignoring its noble mission to be responsible for world 
peace and security, it will be a shame to history. 
  Originally, the basis for the existence of an international 
organization is impartiality. 
  If the IAEA Secretariat and the UN Security Council, bereft 
of impartiality, continue to insist on pressure with an 
unreasonable attitude, we will not feel any need to be 
restricted by such pressure, either. 
  It is intolerable that we have suffered from big obstacles 
in 
our peaceful nuclear activities, restricted by the unilateral 
demand of the IAEA. In case pressure is put on us again, we 
will no longer fall victim to the unreasonable demand but will 
have to go our own way, unhindered by anything. 
  This is our firm will, who regard independence as our life 
and blood. 
  If some officials of the IAEA Secretariat declare that the 
technical possibilities of the future measurement of fuel rods 
are gone or the UN Security Council puts pressure on us, talking 
about sanctions under that pretext, we cannot but take the 
course of taking decisive countermeasures, freeing ourselves 
from such unreasonable restrictions rather than suffering from 
them, and we will be left with no other choice but to go over to 
the continuous process of the peaceful nuclear activities. We 
will respond any time with utmost sincerity to the intention to 
solve the issue in a fair way and resolve it in a peaceful way 
through dialogue. But we will counter without slightest 
compromise even the slightest intention to ignore our 
sovereignty by unjustifiably putting pressure on us. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27500 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas106_c_94012" </HT>


