<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Chong-il Sends Birthday Table to Japanese Woman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Chong-il Sends Birthday Table to Japanese Woman </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK3005050894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0457 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3005050894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 30 (KCNA) -- The dear leader Comrade 
Kim Chong-il sent a birthday table to a Japanese woman Choe Sun 
residing in the central district, Pyongyang Municipality, on her 
70th birthday. 
  Choe Sun (Japanese name: Toshiko Motohasi) was born in May 
1924 in Suminami Ward, Tokyo metropolis, as the eldest daughter 
of a railway worker Eisuke Motohasi, her father, and Haru 
Motohasi, her mother. 
  After graduating from a girls high school, she worked at a 
farm machinery factory before she came to the Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea in January 1960 with her Korean 
husband, Choe Sang-chol, who was chairman of the Suminami branch 
of the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan 
(Chongnyon). 
  After finishing the course of a university, she has taught 
at 
the Pyongyang University of foreign languages, writing many 
books for teaching and training hundreds of foreign language 
experts. 
  Comrade Kim Chong-il made her an assistant professor and 
gave 
her the noble political integrity as a member of the Workers' 
Party of Korea, highly appreciating her services. 
  Receiving the birthday table imbued with loving care amid 
the 
blessings of all peoples on May 27, she said she owed it 
entirely to the politics of grace and the politics of love and 
trust in this land that she is enjoying such worth and happiness 
of life today, she who once lived in a capitalist society where 
the jungle law prevails. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

