<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Reaction to DPRK Nuclear Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kakizawa Calls For Chinese Help </H4>

<F P=102> OW0206033494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0324 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0206033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 2 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa told a senior Chinese official Thursday [2 Jun] the 
situation regarding North Korea's suspected development of 
nuclear weapons is at a critical stage, ministry officials said. 
  "Inspections (of North Korea's nuclear facilities) are 
becoming increasingly difficult. The situation is at an 
important stage and is tense," the officials quoted Kakizawa as 
telling Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan. 
  In a 15-minute meeting with the Chinese visitor, the 
Japanese 
foreign minister repeated calls for China's cooperation in 
solving the problem, adding he wants to hold close consultations 
with China. 
  Tang told Kakizawa China has been making efforts to seek a 
breakthrough on the problem and will continue to make its utmost 
efforts to peacefully solve it through dialogue, adding China's 
approach to North Korea has limits, the officials said. 
  The resumption of dialogue among North Korea, the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and the United States 
is important in seeking a breakthrough to the standoff, Tang was 
saying. 
  He also reiterated China's basic stance that it supports 
denuclearization of the Korean peninsula, and maintenance of 
peace and stability in the region. 
  China played a "constructive role" in compiling the UN 
Security Council's presidential statement issued Monday, Tang 
said. 
  The council statement "strongly" urged Pyongyang to 
cooperate 
in pulling spent fuel rods from a nuclear reactor so IAEA 
inspectors could determine if any material has been diverted for 
nuclear weapons. 
  Tang delivered an invitation from Chinese Foreign Minister 
Qian Qichen for Kakizawa to visit China. 
  If unable to make the trip, the two foreign ministers may be 
able to meet at a meeting of foreign ministers from the 
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and its dialogue 
partners in July, or at an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation 
(APEC) meeting in Jakarta in November, Tang quoted Qian as 
saying. 

</TEXT>

