<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Waste Plant Project With Russia Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Waste Plant Project With Russia Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0206113994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1113 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0206113994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 2 KYODO -- Japan and Russia will soon 
announce plans to build a disposal plant for liquid nuclear 
waste near Vladivostok in the Russian Far East, Foreign Ministry 
sources said Thursday [2 June]. 
  The plant, to be funded from a Japanese 70 million dollar 
grant for denuclearization, is expected to be completed within 
this year, the sources said. 
  The Japanese Government has agreed in principle to construct 
the facility, which would filter radioactive substances from the 
liquid waste, on an offshore dock as requested by Moscow. 
  For lack of storage and treatment facilities the former 
Soviet Union and Russia have been dumping hundreds of tons of 
nuclear waste in the Sea of Japan and other waters off its 
coasts. 
  The disclosure of the decades-long nuclear dumping has 
sparked international protests and strained relations between 
Tokyo and Moscow. 
  Japan last autumn offered to lend Russia a tanker to provide 
urgently needed storage capacity, but Moscow later retreated 
from the plan and proposed to build the waste disposal plant 
instead. 
  Moscow repeatedly told Japan it would have to resume nuclear 
dumping at sea if the plant was not built quickly. 
  The sources said final approval for the project might still 
be held up by apparent differences between Moscow and 
Vladivostok authorities about the nature of the plant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

