<H3> <TI>   Finnish Company Seeks 20% of Cellular Phone Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finnish Company Seeks 20% of Cellular Phone Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0106055294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0533 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0106055294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 1 KYODO -- Finnish mobile phone maker 
Nokia aims to capture a 20 percent share in Japan's digital 
cellular phone market, a senior company official said Wednesday 
[1 June]. 
  Nokia Vice President Jouko Hayrynen told KYODO NEWS SERVICE 
he expects Japan to become a trendsetter in Asia's mobile phone 
market as seen by the boom that followed the government's 
decision to allow makers to retail instead of lease their 
products. Helped by the deregulation, the number of mobile 
phone suppliers in Japan has since doubled to more than 25. 
  Nokia, the world's second-largest mobile phone maker after 
Motorola Inc. of the United States, will finish preparations for 
volume production of models tailored to the Japanese market by 
the end of this month, Hayrynen said. Hayrynen said the 
Japanese mobile phone market is estimated at 1.3 million to 1.5 
million units this year, of which about 50 percent will be 
digital machines. 

</TEXT>

