<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Doyukai Urges Smooth Implementation of Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Doyukai Urges Smooth Implementation of Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0106032594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0311 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0106032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 1 KYODO -- The Japan Association of 
Corporate Executives (Keizai Doyukai) on Wednesday [1 Jun] 
requested anew that the Japanese Government make further efforts 
to smoothly implement political, economic and administrative 
reforms. 
  Chairman Masaru Hayami made the request during a breakfast 
meeting with International Trade and Industry Minister Eijiro 
Hata and other trade ministry officials. 
  Electorate seat redistribution, as part of political 
reforms, 
should be completed during the current parliamentary session 
while a tax reform package containing tax cuts and an offsetting 
consumption tax increase two or three years later should be 
formulated soon, Hayami said, echoing the voice of about 35 
other corporate executives present at the breakfast meeting. 
  Hayami also urged the government to take concrete measures 
to 
narrow a price gap between home and abroad, reduce Japan's huge 
current account surplus, upgrade the labor market and revise a 
spending plan for public works projects for an efficient fund 
allocation. 
  Trade Minister Hata replied that the government will do its 
utmost to address the requests but refrained from making clear 
commitments on specific requests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

