<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chip Makers Positive on FY '94 Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chip Makers Positive on FY '94 Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005055594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0516 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3005055594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 30 KYODO -- Japan's six major electric 
machinery makers plan to spend 15.4 percent more on business 
investment for semiconductor production in fiscal 1994 than they 
did the previous year, according to their projections. 
  The six concerns -- Hitachi Ltd., Fujitsu Ltd., NEC Corp., 
Toshiba Corp., Mitsubishi Electric Corp. and Oki Electric 
Industry Co. -- set aside a total of 461 billion yen for 
investment for the fiscal year that ends March 31, 1995, up from 
399.6 billion yen the year before. 
  Industry officials cited an unabated personal computer boom 
in the United States and bright prospects for domestic demand as 
factors behind the bullish spending plans. 
  The bulk of these investment is targeted at memory chips, 
for 
which demand is shifting from 4-megabit dynamic random access 
memory (dram) chips to 16-megabit dram chips. 
  "The shift in demand for 16-megabit dram chips will be put 
into top gear" in the latter half of this year, said Hajime 
Sasaki, managing director at NEC. 
  NEC, now an industry leader in 16-megabit dram chips, 
expects 
to raise manufacturing capacity to 3 million units a month by 
next March from the current one million. 
  Hitachi is trying to catch up with NEC in the 16-megabit 
dram 
chip market with a project to raise monthly capacity at one of 
its main domestic chip factories to 3 million units, also by 
next March. 
  Fujitsu's investment plan calls for investing more than 100 
billion yen, its first such layout in three years, while Toshiba 
and Mitsubishi plan to increase investment for the first time in 
three years after keeping their investments flat for the past 
two years. 
  Oki, which returned to profitability in the latest business 
year ended March 31, expects to double its investment for chip 
production. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

