<F P=102>   OW0106140894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1322 GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0106140894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 1 KYODO -- The Food Agency has exerted 
pressure on a major rice wholesaler not to protest the 
government's food control policies, it was learned Wednesday [1 
June]. 
  The agency asked Bunji Nakamura, president of Yamatane 
Corp., 
to keep the company's outspoken chairman Seizo Yamazaki from 
making provocative remarks against Japan's food control system, 
in which the government keeps a tight grip on production and 
marketing of rice. 
  The agency made the request on March 16 when it called 
Nakamura to ask for Yamatane's cooperation in sales of imported 
rice. 
  The agency denied the accusation, but other reports said 
that 
it has asked members of farm ministry panels and food-services 
industry officials not to criticize the government's policies. 

