<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy Reportedly Hints at NPT Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Envoy Reportedly Hints at NPT Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0206020294 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0105 GMT 2 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0206020294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mun Chae-chol from Washington] </F>
  [Text] North Korea hinted that it would withdraw from the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty if the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA] officially declares that the possibility of 
the further measurement of fuel rods is dissipated, or the UN 
Security Council takes steps to impose sanctions on North Korea. 
  A high-level official of the North Korean Mission to the 
United Nations, in quoting the statement by the North Korean 
Foreign Ministry, said that if some circles of the IAEA declare 
that the possibility for the further measurement of the nuclear 
fuel rods has dissipated technically, or the UN Security Council 
pressures North Korea by imposing sanctions, North Korea will 
take a decisive step to deal with them, rather than suffer from 
their unreasonable steps. Therefore, he hinted at the 
possibility that North Korea would withdraw from the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. 
  Also, he admitted that North Korea accelerated the speed of 
the work to replace the nuclear fuel rods some time ago in order 
to test the maximum efficiency of the machine that carries out 
the work. 

</TEXT>

