<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Ambassador: Sanctions `Inevitable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nuclear Ambassador: Sanctions `Inevitable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0206045094 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0300 GMT 2 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0206045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government is reportedly pushing for a United 
Nations resolution to impose sanctions on North Korea right 
after holding consultations with the United States and others in 
case North Korea has removed the possibility for future 
measurements by continuing to replace fuel rods. 
  Kim Sam-hun, nuclear ambassador, who left the country on 2 
June to have a three-day policy consultations between the ROK, 
the United States, and Japan in Washington, pointed out that 
warning measures have sufficiently been taken up until now. He 
added that the government's position is that it is now 
inevitable to take measures related to the imposition of 
sanctions against the North. 
  Since our government, the United States, and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency have so far made many efforts 
for dialogue, Ambassador Kim Sam-hun said, it will also be 
difficult for China to offer opposition if a resolution for 
sanctions is discussed at the United Nations. 

</TEXT>

