<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Commission Mulls Antidumping Charges </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    European Commission Mulls Antidumping Charges </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2705035494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0038 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2705035494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, May 26 (YONHAP) -- The European Union (EU) 
Commission said Thursday it was considering whether to extend 
anti-dumping tariffs on video cassettes made in South Korea and 
Hong Kong that are due to expire in June. 
  The commission is investigating charges by the European 
Council of Chemical Manufacturers Federation (CEFIC), which has 
expressed concern that the two countries may continue to export 
their products at unfair prices in view of their ample 
manufacturing potential. 
  The CEFIC charges that Korean and Hong Kong video cassettes 
are sold at one-third the price of European products and that 
their dumping margins were actually greater than the 
anti-dumping tariff rates imposed. The EU has imposed punitive 
duties of 1.9 percent on Saehan Media, 3.8 percent on Sunkyong, 
2 percent on Kolon and 2.9 percent on Goldstar since June 1989. 
  Under the sunset provision, tariff imposition automatically 
terminates after five years unless the industry in the host 
country calls for an extension. 

</TEXT>

