<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties To Announce Merge </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parties To Announce Merge </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2905092194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0844 GMT 29 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2905092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 29 (YONHAP) -- The United People's Party 
(UPP) and the New Political Reform Party (NPRP) will merge into 
one on Monday. 
  UPP leader Kim Tong-kil and NPRP leader Pak Chan-chong will 
have a joint press conference at the National Assembly Monday 
morning to announce their union. 
  Kim and Pak will say that their union does not mean giving 
up 
full-scale union of the opposition parties, but it is rather a 
first stage aiming at union of all the opposition parties in the 
future, including the main opposition Democratic Party and New 
Korea Party. 
  The unified party, whose name is not decided yet, will also 
try to admit independent lawmakers to be a formal negotiating 
body in the National Assembly. 
  Now UPP has 12 lawmakers and NPRP has one, so according to 
the rules of the National Assembly, the unified party will be 
able to be a negotiating body if seven lawmakers join it in 
addition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

