<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Turkmenistan President's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Turkmenistan President's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Radio Comments on Results </H4>

<F P=102> BK0106134094 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0810 
GMT 1 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0106134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary] </F>
  [Text] Although it is Turkmenistan President Saparmurad 
Niyazov's first visit to Malaysia, considerable headway was 
achieved in ties with Malaysia. The five bilateral agreements 
signed in various fields are vital as they will pave the way to 
enhance two-way cooperation. This is all the more significant 
as the breakaway Soviet Union state only achieved independence 
three years ago. 
  Therefore, there is much the Central Asian nation can learn 
from Malaysia. As can be seen from the deteriorating situation 
in Russia, the transition towards a market-based economy is not 
all that easy. It is important that the right economic policies 
and development strategies are in place. To this end, Malaysia 
is ready to offer its expertise wherever it is possible in the 
spirit of South-South cooperation. 
  With a population of 4.2 million people, Turkmenistan is 
rich 
in oil and gas reserves, minerals, cotton, and chemical 
properties. This provides excellent prospects for the 
development of downstream activities -- an area where Malaysia 
has excelled in. The national oil corporation Petronas can look 
into tapping the oil and gas reserves besides looking to develop 
petrochemicals in Turkmenistan. Other areas for potential joint 
ventures include hotel construction, resort facilities, and 
tourism. But the former Soviet state has to realize that 
foreign investments do not flow into a country automatically. 
It must work towards creating a conducive investment climate. 
Red tape must be cut to a minimum. Bureaucracy has been a 
major obstacle for cross-border investments. 
  This is often the case in developing countries. So far, 
Turkmenistan's legislation which provides for foreign 
investments is a step in the right direction. Its free economic 
zones is yet another indicator that its investment strategy is 
on the right track. Infrastructure facilities have to be well 
in place, otherwise foreigners will be reluctant to invest. It 
also has to realize that competition for the foreign investment 
dollar is getting more intense. Also, its private sector has 
yet to fully develop its potential. 
  There is much it can learn from Malaysia's success in 
privatization. It is important that the development of private 
enterprises is accompanied by social benefits. Otherwise a wide 
cross section of the people will never taste the fruits of 
economic development and might sow the seeds of discontent. 
Malaysia is ready to offer training aid under the Malaysia 
technical cooperation program in administration, banking, and 
other fields. It has trained officers under this program from 
numerous other developing nations. It forms part of Malaysia's 
commitment towards transferring skills to South countries. 
  Turkmenistan's decision to establish an embassy in Malaysia 
marks a major step in building a concrete bridge towards 
enhancing two-way contacts at the highest level. This would go 
a long way in bringing bilateral links to a more significant 
level. 
  Niyazov's visit, which comprises a high-powered delegation, 
indicates the importance the country places in its relationship 
with Malaysia. The visit has also opened a new chapter in what 
is potentially a mutually beneficial and long-lasting 
relationship between Malaysia and Turkmenistan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27632 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas106_h_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-106 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mahathir, PRC's Li Peng Exchange Notes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mahathir, PRC's Li Peng Exchange Notes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0106133994 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 31 
May 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0106133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Mon. [30 May] -- The bilateral 
relations between Malaysia and China have reached a new level of 
understanding and cooperation, and the two countries should take 
pride in the steady development, Datuk Sri Dr. Mahathir Mohamed 
said. 
  He said in the last five years, bilateral relations had 
increased by leaps and bounds in many fields of cooperation. 
  "I am confident this trend will be further reinforced in the 
years to come," he said in a two-page letter to Chinese Premier 
Li Peng on the occasion of the 20th anniversary of diplomatic 
ties between the two countries. His letter was released by 
Wisma Putra [Foreign Ministry]. 
  Formal ties were sealed in Beijing on May 31, 1974 by the 
late Tun Abdul Razak, then Malaysian Prime Minister, and his 
then Chinese counterpart the late Zhou Enlai. 
  Dr. Mahathir paid tribute to Razak's vision and courage in 
making Malaysia the first ASEAN country to normalise ties with 
China. 
  "I believe credit for the development of the excellent 
relations between Malaysia and China should also go to the 
pragmatic and outward-looking leadership of China," he said. 
  He said the policy of friendly relations with neighbouring 
countries had encouraged positive developments in bilateral 
relationships, particularly in recent years. 
  Both Malaysia and China could take pride in the steady 
development of mutually satisfying relations over the last two 
decades although links between them actually go back a long way 
in history, he added. 
  Apart from the rapid increase in economic cooperation, 
trade, 
and investment, Dr. Mahathir said cooperation in other fields 
such as tourism, cultural exchanges, and people-to-people 
contacts would further encourage better understanding and 
friendship. 
  Foreign Minister Datuk Abdullah Ahmad Badawi also sent a 
message on the occasion to his Chinese counterpart and Vice 
Premier Qian Qichen. 
  Li, in a congratulatory message to Dr. Mahathir, said both 
China and Malaysia were developing countries with similar 
historical experiences and were now facing the great tasks of 
developing the national economy. 
  "The seeds of Sino-Malaysian friendship sowed 20 years ago 
have now yielded rich fruits. I am convinced that the tree of 
our friendship that is being fostered will grow even healthier 
in the years to come." 
  Noting Dr. Mahathir's three visits to China in recent years, 
the Chinese premier said the visits had promoted mutual 
understanding and trust and brought Sino-Malaysian relations to 
a new stage of all-round development. The economic and trade 
cooperation between the two countries had now made remarkable 
achievements, he said. 
  "It has been proven by facts that the maintenance of 
friendly 
and good neighbourly relations between China and Malaysia is not 
only in conformity to the fundamental interests of the two 
countries, but also conducive to the peace, stability, and 
prosperity of the region." 
  Qian sent a similar message to Abdullah expressing the hope 
that the existing strong relations between the two countries 
would continue to be consolidated in the future. 
  "We highly regard your government for upholding justice and 
speaking out from a sense of justice in international affairs 
and promoting the political stability and economic prosperity of 
this region," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

