<H3> <TI>   DA Trying To Verify Report on DPRK Laying Mines </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DA Trying To Verify Report on DPRK Laying Mines </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0306043894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 3 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0306043894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 2 Jun Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] Having been informed on 1 June that the DPRK (North 
Korea) could have layed sea mines off the east coast of that 
country, the Defense Agency [DA] is trying to verify the 
information and has begun collecting related details. 
  Information on the laying of sea mines was reported by the 
U.S. ABC television network. According to DA officials 
concerned, when a U.S. reconnaissance satellite witnessed North 
Korea conducting launch tests for its "Silkworm" anti-ship 
missile on 31 May, the satellite witnessed the presence of what 
looked like mine-laying vessels within North Korea's territorial 
waters off its east coast. The satellite also witnessed the 
frequent flight of airplanes around the vessels. Consequently, 
the possibility that sea mines have been laid was pointed out. 
  The DA said: "We cannot verify the information on the laying 
of sea mines on our own. But, if it turns out to be true, then 
we have no choice but to be gravely concerned." The agency is 
thought to have obtained copies of satellite pictures of the 
scene from U.S. military authorities and to be analyzing them at 
present. The agency is also believed to be hurrying with 
analysis of communications information collected from radar 
sites. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

