<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Fear Criticism for Missing OECD Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Fear Criticism for Missing OECD Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0306111394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 3 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0306111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Officials at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs 
[MOFA], the Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI], 
and other relevant government ministries and agencies are 
wracking their brains over the likelihood of Japanese ministers 
being absent at the OECD ministerial meeting to be held in Paris 
7-8 June. It will be the first time since 1967 that not a 
single minister will be present at the meeting. As the 50th 
anniversary commemoration of the D-Day, which led to eventual 
allied victory in World War II, is scheduled around the same 
time, European and U.S. leaders will be gathering in France. 
Although Japan has been an OECD member for 30 years this year, 
it may end up with receiving cold treatment by other nations. 
  Japan joined the OECD in 1964. It has sent either a foreign 
minister, trade minister, or economics minister to the annual 
OECD ministerial meetings from 1968. From 1984, all three 
ministers from the MOFA, MITI, and the Economic Planning Agency 
have, as a rule, participated in the annual ministerial meetings. 
  "Employment and Growth" is the major topic in the agenda of 
the upcoming ministerial meeting. U.S. cabinet-level economics 
officials, including Mickey Kantor, U.S. trade representative, 
Lloyd Bentsen, secretary of treasury, Robert Reich, secretary of 
labor, and Laura Tyson, chairman of the Council of Economic 
Advisers, will all gather at the meeting. U.S. President Bill 
Clinton is also scheduled to be in France around the same time. 
It is expected that a series of meetings will be held, taking 
advantage of the OECD forum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27704 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas107__a94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-107-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MAFF Said To Lift Ban on U.S. Apple Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MAFF Said To Lift Ban on U.S. Apple Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0206094694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0206094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the routine Japan-U.S. talks on plant quarantine 
held in Tokyo, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry, and 
Fisheries [MAFF] has studied quarantine measures to lift the 
existing ban on imports of U.S.-produced apples, and has 
concluded that there should be no danger of blight worms coming 
in with the imported apples. 
  In the recent talks, the ministry has become convinced that 
there is no problem with the United States' insecticidal and 
disinfecting technologies, as well as with its inspection 
methods. A similar judgment has been passed by the United 
States on the Japan-produced apples. Accordingly, it has become 
certain that the ban on trade regarding apples between the two 
countries will be lifted. The MAFF intends to hold public 
hearings during the coming summer and to decide on formal 
lifting of the ban by autumn. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

